Object_being_photographed: Quarter new moon at 22.00 hours last night, 15th June
Device_Model: iPhone SE rear camera through telescope

observation_notes: Setting full moon behind hill, trees silhouetted, about two miles away, about 04.45 on the morning of 27th May 2021
Device_Model: Using my 120mm f5.8 refractor with iPhone rear facing camera

observation_notes: Taken during the J&S Conjunction of 2020. Equipment: Z8, Celestron NexYZ mount, Explore Scientific 14mm 82 deg, iphone7+, Nightcap photo app.
Z8, NexYz smartphone mount, iPhone7+ and Nightcap photo app.

Taken using an Astrozap full aperture solar filter, iPhone7+ using a Celestron NexYz phone mount and NightCap app to dim the object and manipulate the exposure and iso settings. Note the sunspot in the 5 o'clock position and the partial eclipse (plane)^^.

This photo was actually taken with an iPhone 7+ using a Celestron NexYz phone mount on Zhunell 8x42 binoculars held with  steady hands. NightCap app to dim the object and manipulate the exposure and iso settings.
Handheld shot.

I experimented taking some photographs of the planet Venus as it moved through its different phases - after being surprised that my new 4.75 inch, f5.8 refractor from Meade could handle the intense light, and stray light beams, better than my 4 inch apochromatic refractor costing more than twice the money! I am guessing that they must have done a good job with designing the internal baffling at Meade. I took this photograph using a 12mm ED eyepiece and again using the telephoto facility on the rear camera of my iPhone SE. This was another of my photographs that I took looking through my window! I took this photo at 21.30 on the 22nd April, last year.

I took this photograph quite sometime ago, on the 13th February, 2019, at 11.59pm, using my iPhone SE rear camera looking through a 4mm eyepiece on my 102mm f7 apochromatic refractor, also adjusting the telephoto lens on the iPhone camera.

I have experimented with taking a number of photographs through my optical instruments, using both my iPhone and iPad. This photograph is certainly not the sharpest image I have taken, but as it is the most recent, and the crescent new moon is such lovely image, I thought that I would post it on the site
Handheld shot.
Handheld shot
Handheld shot
Mounted shot, using Celestron NexYZ
Bortle 3 zone, altitude 3300 feet, slight editing in Adobe Photoshop Elements
The star was twinkling meaning atmosphere was not stable. Without automated tracker, 1 second is the max exposure I can get without seeing star trails

Image of the Sun and the large sunspot on the Sun's southeast limb. Warning! You must have a properly filtered telescope to image the Sun! I used the Open Cam smartphone app for Android to capture the images.

Experimenting with some camera settings and apps while the Smart Phone was attached to a Williams Optics 66mm Refractor (f/6). This was about 50 minutes after the nearly Full Moon had risen (99.5% Illuminated). I just happened to capture a jet plane crossing the Moon. This image was captured with the "Open Camera" app for Android.

Telescope: Orion StarBlast II 4.5 EQ

Telescope: Celestron C11 HD Edge f/10 Schmidt-Cassegrain on a CGX-L CGEM tracking mount mount
Eyepiece: Televue Radian 18-mm, 60-degree AFOV
Magnification: 155x
Camera/Automatic Processing: Google Pixel 4XL
Exposure Time: 4 minute exposure (automatic selection)
Image Processing: Adobe Lightroom; Cropped image to incorporate only the pupil; maximized contract to blacken the background.

- The atmospheric seeing was excellent this evening to see fine features.
- The telescope used for this image was a Celestron C11 HD Edge f/10 SCT on a CGX-L GEM tracking mount.
- Used the Pixel 4XL's normal camera capability to produce the image.  Also applied a 1.6x optical zoom to get an image that did not show vignetting from the eyepiece pupil.  
- The final image was only flipped via image proccessing software to remove the image orientation produced by the optical system.
Object_being_photographed: Moon - Craters: Plato and Archimedes; Mount Pico

observation_notes: Image was taken with a waxing gibbous Moon high in the sky (approximately 80% illumination).  The telescope used for this image was a Celestron C11 HD Edge f/10 SCT on a CGX-L GEM tracking mount.  Used the Pixel 4XL's astrophotography capability to produce an image.  The exposure/processing time for the phone to yield the raw image was 4:00 minutes.  The included raw image shows vignetting from the eyepiece pupil.  Used Adobe Lightroom to crop, flip, rotate, and do some light image processing. I wanted to reduce the effects of moon glow coming from the eyepiece.  The final image shows the nebula oriented match normal vision.

- First usage of the Google astrophotography capability on their smartphone.
- Total exposure and processing time by phone was approximately 3.5 to 4 minutes.
- Light streaks underneath Orion were from a plane turning into my FOV during the last 15 seconds of the exposure.
- Used Adobe Lightroom to only increase the contrast to reduce the effects of light pollution/sky glow along the horizon.
Object_being_photographed: Orion, the Hyades, the Pleiades, and Venus
